    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="1797"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1797">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 823.00/118.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Peruvian Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peruvian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 5, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform you that I am in
                    receipt of a cable despatch from Lima stating that public opinion and the action
                    of the army in enforcing respect to the Constitution had brought about a change
                    in the Government; that President Billinghurst had resigned the presidency; and
                    that the Senate and House of Deputies jointly by an unanimous vote had entrusted
                    the Executive power to a Provisional Junta of Government composed of the
                    following personnel: President of the Junta and Minister of War and Marine,
                    Colonel Oscar Benavides; Minister of the Interior, Señor Arturo Osores; Minister
                    of Finance, Señor José Balta; Minister of Justice and Education, Senor Rafael
                    Grau; Minister of Public Works, Senor Benjamín Boza; Minister of Foreign
                    Affairs, Senor Jose Matfas Manzanilla.</p>
                <p>The Junta has sworn allegiance to the Constitution, and entered upon its duties
                    as the Executive Power of the Republic; the situation is once more normal and
                    general confidence prevails.</p>
                <p>The members of the Provisional Junta represent the different political parties in
                    Congress, and consequently its constitution will be well received by the
                    nation.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">F. A. Pezet</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
